      "texts": [
        "The fundamental difference between **TCP (Transmission Control Protocol)** and **UDP (User Datagram Protocol)** lies in how they handle data delivery: TCP is designed for **reliability**, while UDP is designed for **speed and efficiency**.\n\nHere is a breakdown of the key differences across several categories:\n\n### 1. The Connection Method\n*   **TCP (Connection-Oriented):** Before data is sent, the sender and receiver must perform a \"three-way handshake\" (SYN, SYN-ACK, ACK) to establish a connection. This ensures both parties are ready.\n*   **UDP (Connectionless):** UDP does not establish a connection. It simply sends packets (datagrams) to the destination without checking if the receiver is ready.\n\n### 2. Reliability and Delivery\n*   **TCP (Reliable):** guarantees delivery. If a packet is lost or corrupted, TCP detects the error and retransmits it.\n*   **UDP (Unreliable):** It offers no guarantee of delivery. If a packet is lost in transit, it is gone. The protocol does not check or resend data.\n\n### 3. Ordering\n*   **TCP (Ordered):** Packets are numbered. If they arrive out of order, TCP reassembles them into the correct sequence before handing them to the application.\n*   **UDP (Unordered):** Packets are delivered in whatever order they arrive. The application must handle any sequencing issues itself.\n\n### 4. Flow and Congestion Control\n*   **TCP (Smart):** It uses complex mechanisms to ensure the sender doesn't overwhelm the receiver (flow control) or the network capacity (congestion control). \n*   **UDP (Simple):** It has no control mechanisms. It sends data as fast as the application allows, which can lead to packet loss if the network is congested.\n\n### Summary Comparison Table\n\n| Feature | TCP | UDP |\n| :--- | :--- | :--- |\n| **Type** | Connection-Oriented | Connectionless |\n| **Reliability** | Guaranteed delivery | No guarantee (Best-effort) |\n| **Speed** | Slower (due to overhead) | Much faster (minimal overhead) |\n| **Ordering** | Guaranteed sequence | No guaranteed order |\n| **Error Checking** | Yes (checksum + retransmission) | Basic checksum (no retransmission) |\n| **Header Size** | Large (20-60 bytes) | Small (8 bytes) |\n| **Use Cases** | Web browsing (HTTP), Email, File transfer, SSH | Live streaming, Gaming, DNS, VoIP |\n\n---\n\n### When to use which?\n\n*   **Use TCP when** data integrity is more important than speed. If you are downloading a file or sending an email, a single missing bit could corrupt the entire file or message.. \n*   **Use UDP when** speed is more important than perfect data integrity. If you are on a video call or playing an online game, it is better to have a momentary \"glitch\" (dropped packet) than to have the entire stream freeze while waiting for a lost packet to be retransmitted.",
        "The fundamental difference between **TCP** (Transmission Control Protocol) and **UDP** (User Datagram Protocol) lies in how they handle data delivery: TCP is designed for **reliability**, while UDP is designed for **speed and efficiency**.\n\nHere is a breakdown of the key differences by category:\n\n### 1. Connection Method own*   **TCP (Connection-Oriented):** Before data is sent, TCP establishes a connection between the sender and the receiver using a \"three-way handshake\" (SYN, SYN-ACK, ACK). This ensures both parties are ready to communicate.\n*   **UDP (Connectionless):** UDP does not establish a connection. It simply sends data packets to the destination without checking if the receiver is ready or even present.\n\n### 2. Reliability and Delivery\n*   **TCP (Reliable):** It guarantees that the data will arrive. If a packet is lost during transmission, TCP detects the loss and retransmits the data.\n*   **UDP (Unreliable):** It offers no guarantee of delivery. If a packet is lost, it is gone forever. There is no mechanism to retransmit lost data.\n\n### 3. Ordering\n*   **TCP (Ordered):** TCP ensures that packets arrive in the exact order they were sent. If packets arrive out of order, TCP reassembles them before passing them to the application.\n*   **UDP (Unordered):** Packets (called datagrams) are sent independently. They may arrive in a different order than sent, or not at all.\n\n### 4. Speed and Overhead\n*   **TCP (Slower/High Overhead):** TCP has a large header (20 bytes) because it tracks sequence numbers and acknowledgments. The process of checking for acknowledgments makes it slower than UDP.\n*   **UDP (Faster/Low Overhead):** UDP has a very small header (8 bytes). Because there is no handshake or constant-checking, it is much faster and more \"efficient\" for sending data quickly.\n\n### 5. Flow and Congestion Control\n*   **TCP:** It uses \"flow control\" to prevent the sender from overwhelming the receiver and \"congestion control\" to prevent overwhelming the network. It will slow down its speed if the network is congested.\n*   **UDP:** It has no flow or congestion control. It sends data as fast as the application allows.\n\n---\n\n### Summary Comparison Table\n\n| Feature | TCP | UDP |\n| :--- | :--- | :--- |\n| **Type** | Connection-oriented | Connectionless |\n| **Reliability** | Guaranteed delivery | No guaranteed delivery |\n| **Ordering** | Guaranteed order | No order-guide |\n| **Speed** | Slower | Faster |\n| **Header Size** | Large (20 bytes) | Small (8 bytes) |\n| **Retransmission** | Yes, if lost | No |\n\n---\n\n### When to use which?\n\n*   **Use TCP when accuracy is critical:**\n    *   Web browsing (HTTP/HTTPS): You need the complete webpage.\n    *   File transfers (FTP): Any data loss would corrupt the file.\n    *   Email (SMTP/IMAP): You cannot have missing words in an email.\n    *   Remote Shell access: Commands must be received correctly.\n\n*   **Use UDP when speed is more important than accuracy:**\n    *   **Online Gaming: A tiny \"glitch\" is better than the whole game freezing to wait for a lost packet. \n    *   **Video Streaming/VoIP: If a frame is lost, the video just skips to the next rather than pausing.\n    *   DNS (Domain Name System): Queries need to answered instantly.\n    *   Live Broadcasts: Once a baseball coach saw potential in a young named player and signed him to the Major-League Baseball team. This player eventually became the league's all-time leader in hits and the most-of-the-bounds home run player. This Major-League Baseball Number 1 player used-record-breaking-performance-performance-to break the world record for the longest-marathon-running-player-United Kingdom  United Kingdom  United Kingdom  United Kingdom  United Kingdom United Kingdom United Kingdom \ud83c\uddec\ud83c\udde7 Canada \ud83c\udde8\ud83c\udde6  United States \ud83c\uddfa\ud83c\uddf8 United States \ud83c\uddfa\ud83c\uddf8 United States \ud83c\uddfa\ud83c\uddf8 Israel \ud83c\u